{
  "card_id": "breakout",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Breakout",
  "aliases": [
    "break",
    "breakout signature",
    "Breakout Signature",
    "突破"
  ],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A price move that aggressively closes beyond a previous swing high or low out of a consolidation or retracement, signaling continuation. Identified by closure (not just a wick) above/below the prior range high or low, followed by expansive directional candles with shallow opposing retracements. Volume confirmation (e.g., 3x average) and sustained directional movement increase reliability.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Price must close beyond the previous swing high (bullish) or swing low (bearish), not merely wick through it.",
    "The breakout closure should emerge from a consolidation or shallow retracement that follows a prior expansion leg.",
    "Following the breakout closure, expect large-range expansion candles with very shallow retracements against the move.",
    "A new opposing candle (protected swing) forming intraday after retesting the opening price confirms the breakout structure.",
    "Distinguish from a consolidation manipulation: a true breakout produces follow-through expansion, not a sweep that reverts back inside the range.",
    "Identify significant horizontal support or resistance levels using pivot points with a long period (e.g., 20) where price has reacted multiple times.",
    "Look for decreasing volatility or a tightening price range as the level is approached, or price action signals like higher lows before an upside breakout.",
    "Confirm the breakout with a notable increase in volume: on standard volume bars, volume should be at least 3x recent average; on a volume footprint, look for net buying (green) above resistance or net selling (red) below support.",
    "Ensure the breakout leads to a sustained directional move away from the level, not a brief spike.",
    "Optionally, a price gap occurring on the breakout reinforces the signal's strength."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "A breakout signals continuation or start of a new trend. Traders enter after price close and volume confirmation, placing stops just inside the broken level (which may become new support/resistance). Hold positions as long as price respects the breakout area, tracking protected swings to manage risk. After roughly three days of expansion into an objective, reassess for retracement or consolidation. High volume, momentum, and gaps increase confidence; low-volume breakouts are less reliable.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Entering a breakout trade without waiting for a decisive price close beyond the level, risking false signals.",
    "Treating a sweep of the prior high/low as a breakout when price did not actually close above it (no closure = no protected swing).",
    "Expecting continued expansion after three days of breakout-driven expansion into an objective instead of anticipating a new phase of price.",
    "Confusing a consolidation manipulation (sweep and revert) with a genuine breakout closure with follow-through.",
    "Entering without volume confirmation, leading to false breakouts.",
    "Relying on a single indicator or signal without additional price action or volume confirmation.",
    "Using too short a minimum range length when defining trading ranges, generating many false signals.",
    "Ignoring overall market context or trend direction when interpreting breakout signals.",
    "Ignoring the tightening of price range or decreased volatility preceding the breakout."
  ],
